         <entryFree xml:id="k000108" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-7" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">goutou</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">勾頭</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">勾头</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">gōutóu</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">kou-t'ou</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-6" xml:lang="en" type="literal_translation">hooked heads (lit.)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000108-1" xml:lang="en" >barrel tile ends</term>
            
            <note type="Note">
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000108-1">A goutou is the <term ref="/keyword/k000109">barrel tile</term> at the bottom of each tile row used to cap the ends (Liang 1981, 78). This term is commonly found in <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasty texts. An earlier term for this element is "<term ref="/keyword/k000110">wadang</term>".
             </p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000108-1">“勾頭”是<term ref="/keyword/k000109">筒瓦</term>每隴最下有圓盤為頭之瓦 （梁 1981，78）。作為蓋瓦用於檐頭以遮擋檐部。<term ref="/keyword/k000051">明</term><term ref="/keyword/k000070">清</term>時期文獻中的勾頭如以前的 "<term ref="/keyword/k000110">瓦當</term>"。
             </p>
          </note>
            <note type="related concepts">
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">瓦 wǎ</p>
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant" ref="/keyword/k000110">瓦當 wǎdàng</p>
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-3" xml:lang="zh-Hant">㼧瓦 tóngwǎ</p>
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-4" xml:lang="zh-Hant" ref="/keyword/k000109">筒瓦 tǒngwǎ</p>
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-5" xml:lang="zh-Hant" ref="/keyword/k000104">瓪瓦 bǎnwǎ</p>
               <p xml:id="related-concept-k000108-6" xml:lang="en">antefixes</p>
            </note>
